Interface PropertyValue

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    TypeDefinitionCharacterImpl.CharacterValue, TypeDefinitionEnumerationImpl.EnumerationValue, TypeDefinitionExtendibleEnumerationImpl.ExtendibleEnumerationValue, TypeDefinitionFixedArrayImpl.FixedArrayValue, TypeDefinitionImpl.PropertyValueImpl, TypeDefinitionIndirectImpl.IndirectValue, TypeDefinitionIntegerImpl.BaseIntegerValue, TypeDefinitionIntegerImpl.ByteValue, TypeDefinitionIntegerImpl.IntegerValue, TypeDefinitionIntegerImpl.LongValue, TypeDefinitionIntegerImpl.ShortValue, TypeDefinitionObjectReferenceImpl.ObjectReferenceValue, TypeDefinitionObjectReferenceImpl.UnresolvedReferenceValue, TypeDefinitionOpaqueImpl.OpaqueValue, TypeDefinitionRecordImpl.RecordValue, TypeDefinitionRenameImpl.RenamedValue, TypeDefinitionSetImpl.SetValue, TypeDefinitionStreamImpl.StreamValue, TypeDefinitionStringImpl.BaseStringValue, TypeDefinitionStringImpl.ByteArrayStringValue, TypeDefinitionStringImpl.CharacterStringValue, TypeDefinitionVariableArrayImpl.VariableArrayValue

    public interface PropertyValue

    Specifies the type and current value of a property. Methods of the subclasses of type definition allow access to the data value held in the property value object.

    See Also:
    TypeDefinition.createValue(Object), PropertyDefinition, getValue()

    • Method Detail

      • getType

        TypeDefinition getType()

        Returns the type definition for this property value.

        Methods of the returned type definition can be used to manipulate a property value. For example, for a value of AAF UInt32 type, the following methods are available on TypeDefinitionInteger:

        • Number getInteger(PropertyValue)
        • PropertyValue createValueFromNumber(Number)
        • void setInteger(PropertyValue, Number)
        Returns:
        Type of this property value.
        See Also:
        PropertyDefinition.getTypeDefinition(), TypeDefinitions.TypeDefinitionWeakReference

      • getValue

        Object getValue()

        Returns the value of the property through a generic Java object interface. Alternative type-specific access methods are provided in each type definition.

        For example, for a property value of a UInt32 type, this method returns an Integer. Values will need to be cast to appropriate types by the application. The value returned may be null, which may indicate that an optional property was not present.

        Returns:
        Value of this property.
        See Also:
        TypeDefinition.createValue(Object)

      • equals

        boolean equals(Object o)

        Tests to see if the this property value and the given object are equal. Two property values are equal if-and-only-if:

        • the given object is not null;
        • the given object is another property value;
        • the given property value has the same type as this one;
        • the values of the given property and this one are equal according to Object.equals(Object) or both property values represent a null value.
        Overrides:
        equals in class Object
        Parameters:
        o - Property value to test equality with this one.
        Returns:
        Is this property value equal to the given property value.
        See Also:
        Object.equals(Object), MediaEngine.deepEquals(MetadataObject, Object)

      • toString

        String toString()

        Creates a string representation of the value contained in this property value. The string "null" is returned for a null value. The type of the value is not included.
